04065nam a22005175i 9780773568310DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20002000xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735683107 a10.1515/97807735683102doi  a(DE-B1597)657516  a(OCoLC)244764387  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aTK1427 Q8bM273 2000eb 7aBUS0000002bisacsh04a333.91/415/09714161 aMassell, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAmassing Power :bJ.B. Duke and the Saguenay River, 1897-1927 /cDavid Massell. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2000] 4c©2000  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies on the History of Quebec/Études d'histoire du Québec ;v1300tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Problem and Its Sources -- tThe River Passes into Private Hands, 1897–1907 -- tA Shift in Scale, 1909–1912 -- tJ.B. Duke, Master Trader, 1912–1914 -- tThe Province Attempts to Keep Pace, 1910–1915 -- tLocal Politics, Big Business, and an Intransigent State: The Fiasco of 1915–1916 -- tA Lake Grant Won, 1916–1922 -- tThe Balance of Power, 1923–1927 -- tConclusion: The Limits to American Investment -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe damming of the Saguenay brought industrialisation on a grand scale to rural Quebec in the form of newsprint and aluminum manufacture. Tapping into rich and diverse sources in Canada, the United States, and Europe, Massell provides an interdisciplinary, cross-border study of American capital and Canadian resources. He shows us how ever-larger amounts of capital yielded increasingly massive and sophisticated applications of hydroelectric technology. Grand industrial plans, in turn, encroached upon provincial water rights and farmers' lands, which drew the attention of the state. He examines the protracted power struggle between public and private interests - between American capitalists and the nascent bureaucracy of the province of Quebec - and describes the origins and evolution of the events that led to state control over hydraulic resources in the province. In doing so he provides vivid portraits of Duke and of Quebec politicians of the period and gives a dramatic account of the protracted battle of wits between Duke's chief engineer, William States Lee, and Quebec's chief of Hydraulic Service, Arthur Amos. Amassing Power speaks to the integration of North American economies, vividly illustrating the process by which American capital drew Canada's resource-rich North into the economic orbit of the United States.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356831040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773568310423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773568310/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles